Yuvi 👌 — the Golden Token problem (Day 84) is a neat greedy + digit manipulation challenge. Let’s break it down clearly.

🔑 Problem Restatement
You’re given a number (token).

You can swap two digits at most once.

Goal: maximize the number’s value.

If the number is already maximal, no swap is needed.

🧩 Approach (Greedy)
Convert the number into a string/array of digits.

For each digit (from left to right):

Find the largest possible digit to the right that can replace it.

If such a digit exists, swap them and stop (since only one swap allowed).

If no beneficial swap is found, return the original number.

👉 This is essentially LeetCode 670 – Maximum Swap.

✅ C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int maximizeToken(int num) {
    string s = to_string(num);
    int n = s.size();

    // Record last occurrence of each digit
    vector<int> last(10, -1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        last[s[i] - '0'] = i;
    }

    // Try to swap
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int curr = s[i] - '0';
        // Look for a larger digit to the right
        for (int d = 9; d > curr; d--) {
            if (last[d] > i) {
                swap(s[i], s[last[d]]);
                return stoi(s);
            }
        }
    }

    return num; // already maximal
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; 
    cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int tokenNumber; 
        cin >> tokenNumber;
        cout << maximizeToken(tokenNumber) << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
